        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The requested RMS is the RMS achieved by using the minimum allowed polarization track (3 hours).

We expect to detect ordered polarization in small (~20 AU) regions.  If dust grains are still aligned within those regions, theories predict the polarization percentage to be as high as 7-10%.  We have conservatively estimated in "Source properties" that the polarization within the small regions will be 3%, but we expect it to be higher.  The RMS we will achieve within the requisite 3-hour polarization observation will allow us to detect 1.4% polarization across most of the disk in IM Lup.
</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The correlator setup is the setup recommended for continuum polarization observations.
</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The dust disk in IM Lup has an extent of 4"; consequently, the entire extent of the dust emission region will lie within the 1/3-power point of the Band 7 primary beam.  

However, recovering dust emission on the largest scales is not critical.  We request 1.4" as the largest angular scale in order to restrict ourselves to one configuration (C36-5): our main focus is on the smallest scale structures (0.14").  We choose this smallest angular scale because it is of order the scale height in the outer disk (~20 AU), which is the scale at which we expect to see coherent, turbulent cells of highly polarized dust emission.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
