    <prp:abstract>Observations of dust polarization allow us to infer magnetic field (B-field) morphologies in star-forming regions, from 100 pc clouds to 100 AU Class 0/I protoplanetary disks.  However, previous interferometric observations have placed stringent upper limits on the polarization fraction in Class II sources, which no longer have infalling envelopes.  The lack of large-scale (~100 AU) polarization in Class II sources is surprising, considering that they form out of highly polarized protostellar envelopes.  However, MHD turbulence is thought to stir up the B-fields in disks, resulting in small-scale eddies where B-fields are ordered and the polarization fraction is high.  If this is the case, the polarization signal would be washed out in at 100 AU resolution, but would be detectible at smaller scales.  Here propose ~20 AU-resolution polarization observations of IM Lup: a nearby source with a bright, extended, optically thin disk, and no residual envelope.  These observations are likely to yield the first detection of polarization in a Class II protoplanetary disk, and are complementary to observations of HL Tau, which is younger, partially embedded, &amp; may be optically thick.</prp:abstract>
